Runing K-means clustering on continuous Variables to determine the number of cluster that seems reasonable and optimal k.

Answer: At this point, the optimal choice is 5 as can be seen from the plot below, cluster 15 is too crownded so cluster 5 looks better. See graphs below for evident. Note: This is not the final optimal k

#Steps in determining the optimal k: Install and run needed packages

Answer: This graph below shows that k=5 was not the best choice afterall, rather 3 is the best and overall choice. Answer optimal k=3

#Testing Whether Our K was Optimal
set.seed(123)
#Scaling the dataframe z-score
fviz_nbclust(uni_con, kmeans, method = "wss")

#Scaling the dataframe silhoutte method
fviz_nbclust(uni_con, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

#Creating the cluster index for 3 clusters
set.seed(123)
k3_median = kcca(uni_con, k=3, kccaFamily("kmedians"))
clusters_index_3 <- predict(k3_median)
#Merging the clusters to the original data frame
set.seed(123)
clusters <- data.frame(clusters_index_3)
clean_Uni <- cbind(Clean_Uni, clusters)
clean_Uni$room_board_fees <- clean_Uni$room + clean_Uni$board + clean_Uni$add..fees + clean_Uni$estim..book.costs + clean_Uni$estim..personal..

C. Compare the summary statistics for each cluster and describe each cluster in this context (e.g., Universities with high tuition, low acceptance rate).

#Summary Statistics for Each Cluster
set.seed(123)
Summary_cont <- clean_Uni %>% 
    group_by( clusters_index_3 ) %>%
    summarise( Acceptance_rate = sum(X..appl..accepted)/ sum(X..appli..rec.d), Avg_out_state_tuition=mean(out.of.state.tuition), Avg_int_state_tuition=mean(in.state.tuition), room_board_fees=mean(room_board_fees), mean_PHD_fac=mean(X..fac..w.PHD), mean_stud_fac_ratio=mean(stud..fac..ratio), mean_grad_rate=mean(Graduation.rate), priv_count = sum(Public..1...Private..2. == 2), pub_count = sum(Public..1...Private..2. == 1))

Answer:Based on table 1 (Summary_cont) which contains information on all the three clusters combined (i.e.cluster1, cluster2, and cluster 3): (a) The mean graduation rate is lowest for cluster 1. (b) The mean student to faculty ratio is lowest for cluster 2. (c) The mean PHD faculty ratio is lowest for cluster 3. (d) The mean room, board, and fees is lowest for cluster 3. (e) The average in state tuition is lowest for cluster 1. (f) The out of state tuition is lowest for 1. (g) The acceptance rate is lowest for cluster 2.

F. Consider Tufts University, which is missing some information. Compute the Euclidean distance of this record from each of the clusters that you found above (using only the measurements that you have). Which cluster is it closest to? Impute the missing values for Tufts by taking the average of the cluster on those measurements.

Answer: Cluster 2 has the lowest distance from Tufts Please see output below.

#F. Isolating the data to Tufts University

library(dplyr)
library(stats)

Tufts <- filter(Uni_all, College.Name == "Tufts University")
Tufts[, -c(1, 2, 3, 10)] <- predict(norm_Tufts, Tufts[, -c(1, 2, 3, 10)])

#Euclidean Distance for Each Clusters: 
#Cluster 1
dist(rbind(Tufts[, -c(1, 2, 3, 10)], k3$centers[1,]))
##          1
## 2 6.053061
#Cluster 2
dist(rbind(Tufts[, -c(1, 2, 3, 10)], k3$centers[2,]))
##          1
## 2 4.695208
#Cluster 3
dist(rbind(Tufts[, -c(1, 2, 3, 10)], k3$centers[3,]))
##          1
## 2 5.894766
#Impute NAs with average from cluster 2
cluster_2 <- filter(clean_Uni, clusters_index_3 == 2)
avg_cluster_2 <- mean(cluster_2[,c(10)])
Tufts[, c(10)] <- avg_cluster_2
Tufts[, c(10)]
